@node features "Features"

                               Features

-There's no complex installation: just run the game and play!

-MLink is a "Workbench" game, so it's meant to be played on the
 Workbench screen. The game window can be resized up to a maximum of
 480 x 300 pixels, and the game is redisplayed according to the new
 window size. If the window is too small, it will be automatically
 resized to the smallest displayable size.

-As the game uses as little of the computer's ressources as possible,
 you can run other applications, games, etc. at the same time.

-MLink works on all Amigas with Workbench 1.3 or higher.

@endnode

@node histo "History"

                               Versions History

  What follows are the various updates that were done since the first version
of this game.

1.0: -First release.

1.1: -No more blitting operations, just simple drawings, it's more friendly
      for blitter handicapped systems (Pegasos/Morphos, Amithlon, etc.)...
      and the display updates (when the game starts or if you resize the
      window) are faster.

1.11: -Some minor changes were made to the program code.
      -Some cosmetic changes were made (the pull-down menus were enhanced,
       the buttons were redrawn).

1.12: -Various changes have been made to the program code: the routine to
       generate the main game window has been revised, unneeded program
       code has been removed, etc.

@endnode

@node play "The game: Installation/Playing"

                             Installation

  The installation is very simple, just place "MLink" where you want 
on your hard drive, floppy disk, Ram Disk, etc. You must have a
Workbench with @{b}8 colours or more@{ub} to play the game, apart from that,
no other files or Libraries are needed.

                             How to play?

  The game consists of 15 coloured chainlinks that were randomly shuffled. You
have to place these chainlinks in the right order, obviously with the top ones
(the upper 'semicircles') on the top, the lower ones (the lower 'semicircles')
below and the intermediate links in between. Of course their colour must match
in each column!

  Note that you don't have to place the chains in a specific colour order from
left to right and the shorter chain can be placed either in the upper or lower
position in its column, as long as its links are joined together.

  Playing with MLink is very simple: just click on one of the arrows, each of
these arrows will move one (or more) chainlink tile(s) in that direction.

  The arrows pointing to the right or left will move all the tiles on that row
by one position in the direction indicated (if you move the tiles to the
right, the rightmost tile will go to the left, and vice-versa if you move the
tiles to the left).

  The arrows pointing up and down are always located on the same column as
where the gap is positioned, so clicking on one of these arrows will move a
tile up or down to that gap, if that move is possible.

  You can restart the game anytime by clicking on the @{b}New Game@{ub} button
(or with the Right-Amiga + "N" key combination).

  Have fun!

@endnode

